#Text=US Congressional panel claims Turkey committed genocide
#Text=Friday , March 5 , 2010
#Text=A United States Congressional panel has passed a resolution describing Turkey 's killing of Armenians in World War I as genocide , over objections from the White House .
#Text=... characterise the systematic and deliberate annihilation of 1.5 million Armenians as genocide — Partial text of the resolution passed yesterday by the House Foreign Affairs Committee

#Text=The panel , the House Foreign Affairs Committee , passed the resolution , which calls on President Barack Obama to " characterize the systematic and deliberate annihilation of 1.5 million Armenians as genocide , " by a vote of 23 to 22 .

column1: #Text=The passage came even after the White House warned the panel that the vote would harm talks between Turkey and Armenia , and US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton asked the panel not to proceed with the vote .
#Text=Additionally , a Turkish parliamentary delegation aimed at convincing panel members to defeat the resolution also had gone to Washington to plead their case .
#Text=Just minutes after the US resolution passed , Turkey issued a statement condemning " this resolution which accuses the Turkish nation of a crime it has not committed . "

column1: #Text=Additionally , Turkey said that their ambassador to the United States had been immediately recalled for consultation .

#Text=Armenians , both in America and overseas , welcomed the vote , however , with the Armenian government calling the passage of the resolution " an important step towards the prevention of crimes against humanity . "

column1: #Text=... accuses the Turkish nation of a crime it has not committed — From a statement issued by the Turkish government in response to the passage of the resolution
#Text=The fallout from the vote threatened to disrupt talks between Turkey and Armenia intended to return the two countries to normal diplomatic status .
#Text=These talks which were acknowledged by President Obama earlier this week in a telephone call to Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan thanking him for his efforts in the negotiations .
#Text=Additionally , the resolution significantly dampens relations between America and Turkey , which is America 's staunchest Muslim ally .

#Text=The US government is dependent on Turkey for its access to northern Iraq , as well as its efforts to regionally isolate Iran , and the government will undoubtedly be working to limit the diplomatic fallout from the resolution .
#Text=... an important step towards the prevention of crimes against humanity — From a statement issued by the Armenian government in response to the passage of the resolution
#Text=The events that prompted the resolution were the deportation of Armenians from the Ottoman Empire , the precursor to the current Turkish state , in 1915 .
#Text=Either disease , starvation or deliberate killings by Turkish troops killed around a million and a half Armenians during the deportations and other events during World War I.
#Text=Since then , more than 20 countries worldwide have officially condemned the actions as genocide .
#Text=Turkey , however , has rejected the term , and maintains that there was no deliberate attempt to annihilate the Armenian people .
